Preheat your oven to 220°C. Chop the @sweet potato{1} into 2cm wide wedges (no need to peel!). Put them on a #baking tray{}, drizzle over a good splash of @olive oil{1%tbsp}, sprinkle over half the @mild paprika{1/2%tsp}, a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a grind of @ground black pepper{1%grind}. Arrange in a single layer on the baking tray and make sure everything is evenly coated. Pop on the top shelf of your oven and cook until soft and golden, ~{25%minutes}. Turn half way through.

Zest the @lime{1} and cut in half. Trim the root from the @baby gem lettuce{1} then half lengthways. Thinly slice widthways and separate the leaves. Peel and grate the @carrot{1%large}, then mix into a #bowl{} with the lettuce. Set aside. Mix the olive oil with a small squeeze of lime juice and a pinch of salt and pepper. Whisk together with a #fork{} then put to one side.

Roughly chop the @coriander{1/2%bunch}(roughly chopped, stalks and all) and roughly chop the @salted peanuts{25%g}. Put the @British pork mince{300%g} in a bowl and add three quarters of your coriander along with your lime zest, peanuts, the other half of the paprika, half the @soy sauce{25%ml} and a good grind of pepper. Mix everything together with your hands and shape into burgers about 2cm thick.

> TIP: You want one burger per person

Put a #frying pan{} on medium heat and add a splash of oil. Add your burgers and cook for ~{5%minutes} on each side, before placing them on a baking tray. Put the burgers in the oven to carry on cooking for ~{5%minutes}. In the meantime, make the sauce. Put the @peanut butter{1%tbsp} in a bowl and add any remaining lime juice to taste. Add a splash of @water{splash} to loosen, then mix in the remaining soy sauce and coriander.

Turn your grill to high and cut each @brioche bun{2} in half. Put your buns under the grill for ~{1-2%minutes} on each side to toast them.

> TIP: If your oven and grill aren't separate, just move your sweet potato and burgers down a shelf so the top shelf is free for grilling!

> TIP: Keep an eye on them, you don't want them to burn!

When everything is ready, spread your satay sauce on the bottom half of the bun, pop the burger on top, add some lettuce and carrot mixture then pop on the other half of the bun. Add the limey dressing to the rest of the carrot and lettuce salad, give it a toss, then serve alongside the burger with your sweet potato wedges. YUM!